<p><b>Eric Hoffer</b> (July 25, 1902 – May 21, 1983) was an American social <a href="/wiki/Writer" title="Writer">writer</a> and philosopher. He produced ten books and was awarded the <a href="/wiki/Presidential_Medal_of_Freedom" title="Presidential Medal of Freedom">Presidential Medal of Freedom</a> in February 1983 by <a href="/wiki/President_of_the_United_States" title="President of the United States">President of the United States</a> <a href="/wiki/Ronald_Reagan" title="Ronald Reagan">Ronald Reagan</a>. His first book, <i><a href="/wiki/The_True_Believer" title="The True Believer">The True Believer</a></i>, published in 1951, was widely recognized as a classic, receiving critical acclaim from both scholars and laymen.<sup id="cite_ref-EB_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-EB-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
